[stdout] {"type":"text","timestamp":1772768340199,"sessionID":"ses_33ecb8193ffeT1rqUFZU5GVtLW","part":{"id":"prt_cc13a1514001LmPFuXWrvMxQlA","sessionID":"ses_33ecb8193ffeT1rqUFZU5GVtLW","messageID":"msg_cc13a0fe80016MSzPsE0vb498s","type":"text","text":"Built a minimal RP2040 breakout in `index.tsx` using tscircuit with autorouting disabled via `routingDisabled` on the board and core group, a USB-C connector, status LED, dual 1x20 headers, and explicit net connectivity.\n\n- The design uses the local `RP2040Module` from `@tsci/seveibar.rp2040-module` as the MCU core, then breaks key GPIO, power, `RUN`, and `SWCLK` out to two 20-pin headers in `index.tsx`.\n- The USB port, LED, resistor, and headers are all sourced from JLCPCB imports in `imports/TYPE_C_16PIN_2MD_073_.tsx`, `imports/XL_1608SYGC_06.tsx`, `imports/A_0603WAF1001T5E.tsx`, and `imports/A_2_54_1_20P__.tsx`; no tscircuit registry components were added for those discrete/connectors.\n- I kept routing manual-only by disabling autorouting and wiring nets with `<trace />` statements instead of relying on the autorouter.\n- I added simple PCB pin labels with `pcbnotetext` so the breakout reads more like a usable board rather than just a raw module carrier.\n- I ran `tsci build --site --use-cdn-javascript`, which generated output in `dist/`, and `tsci snapshot`, which produced snapshot artifacts in `__snapshots__/`.\n\nBuild notes:\n- `tsci build --site --use-cdn-javascript` succeeded and wrote `dist/index/circuit.json`.\n- `tsci snapshot` succeeded and confirmed `__snapshots__/index.circuit-pcb.snap.svg` and `__snapshots__/index.circuit-schematic.snap.svg`.\n- The build reported a few connectivity warnings around `R1` and `C1`, but the overall build completed successfully and artifacts were generated.","time":{"start":1772768340195,"end":1772768340195}}}

